AGI - The Government of South Africa has accused of "campaign and disinformation and propaganda >" the United States, which has ceased to provide funds to the country as a retaliation for a law on land confiscation held by the Trump administration discriminatory against the white minority. The Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Pretoria stated in a note of being "very concerned" for "the basic premise of this decree" that " lacks current accuracy and does not recognize the deep and painful history of colonialism and apartheid of South Africa". The South African Presidency has denied in recent days any intention of "confiscating land" and has explained that the reform provides for the possibility of expropriation without compensation only in cases where this is "right and fair", or, for example, if the areas are abandoned or are not exploited.
&nbsp;
"We are concerned about what seems to be a campaign of disinformation and propaganda aimed at betraying our great nation," said the ministry, "it is disappointing that such narratives seem to find the favor of decision makers in the United States of America". Whites, which are now less than 8% of the South African population, control about 72% of South African agricultural land. &nbsp;
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
Pretoria believes particularly "ironic" that the American decree provides "the granting of refugee status in the United States to a group of South Africans that fall among the most privileged economically", while at the same time "vulnerable people from other parts of the world are expelled in the United States and are denied asylum despite real difficulties". The US decree expressly promises to provide assistance to the "Afrikaner ethnic minority" >, descendant of the first European settlers, also offering them the status of refugees, since the recent South African law on expropriation would be discriminatory against them. This law "will allow the South African government to seize the agricultural properties of the ethnic minority Afrikaner without compensation", denounced Friday Donald Trump in the order that orders the freezing of all funding until the South African government continues "with its unjust and immoral practices". &nbsp;
